args: Hah! Yah! ...Phew! I know there's a juicy\nvein of ore waiting for me if I can just\ncut through this hard bedrock.
Hoo-eee, but ya work like a dog, Gauld!\nMight consider takin' a break there\n'afore yer arms fall off, yessir.
If you want to rest, be my guest.\nThere's juice in these old bones yet.
Consarnit and hornswaggle! Reckon I\nknow now why all the miners here\nlook up to ya like they does!
But are ya sure ya won't rest? 'Cause a\ncertain someone just came by what toâ€”
Here now, listen to me! I'm not made of\nsuch slight stuff that a hard day's work\nwill put me in the grave!
H-hi, Gramps. I, um...made you lunch?
And you're just in time, darling!\nYour old Gramps was just thinking\nabout how tuckered out he was.
Yeee-haw! Who knew a big fella like you\nwould be such a softy for ol' Angie?!
My granddaughter is an angel, and there\nain't an old man around whose heart\nwouldn't melt at the sight of her!
Yer darn tootin' about that! Well, I'm off\nto see to m'own vittles. Hooo-eee! Lunch!
Thanks for showing me how to\nget over here, Mr. Miner!
Um, Gramps? You weren't...mad at me\njust now, were you?
Hee hee! Yay! Okay, then let's eat!
I made a toooon of food for you.\nI hope it's enough.
Well, what a lucky old pickaxe I am,\ngetting to eat homemade food from\nmy lovely little granddaughter...
Gramps, stooop! We eat together\nat home every day!
And that doesn't dim my excitement\none whit. Now let's have a look-see\nat what you whipped up here...
The hell ya think yer doin',\nya sonofa horse's hind end?!
YER the one what wanted a fight!\nI'll kill ya nine ways from Sunday!
It's okay, baby. Gramps's got you.\n...Oh, damn them two rockbrains!
Oy! Knock it off, the both of ya!\nDon't be startin' fights here.
Sit down, old timer, unless ya wanna\npiece of what I'm gonna give HIM!
Yeah, back off, Gauld! Lemme show\nthis dad-sizzle idiot what-for!
Wh-whoa... This old timer's got bite...
S-sorry 'bout that, Gauld. Guess I sorta\nlet my temper get the best of me.
If you get it, then buzz off.\nYou're scaring my granddaughter.
There there, Angie. It's all right now.\nThe scary men are gone.
Really. I'm sorry you had to see that,\nbut it's all going to be fine.
It wasn't your fault, love.\nNo need to go blaming yourself.
You two made it back okay?
Hell, the fault's with me. I didn't tell\nthe new guy 'bout Angie's fits, and...
Poor indeed. It never failsâ€”if she sees\nfolks get violent, she gets the shakes\nlike nothing I've ever seen.
Her body freezes up in fear, like,\nand her breathing gets real hard.
I imagine that kind of thing takes her back\nto the day her ma and pa were killed.
Gotta do what ya must to protect her.\nHell, I get it.
(...But do I have the RIGHT,\nis the question?)
(Do I have the right to embrace a pure\nlittle girl with these bloodstained hands?)
Anyhow, I'm off to sort out the newbies.\nWe can't be havin' fists fly down here!
That boy sure had a short fuse.\nWhat's his deal?
As I hear it, he's got some rotten\nbusiness in his pastâ€”claims he's\nturned over a new leaf, though.
Accordin' to the boss, he was damn near\nbeggin' to work in this here mine.
This mine in particular?\nShady. Mighty shady.
Ilia's beard, Gauld! Quit givin' me\nthe devil's stare, wouldja?
Whenever yer riled, ya get this damn-all\nintense look about ya. Reckon that's what\nput the pins to that fight before.
It's enough to make a man wonder what\ndark shafts ya wandered down in yer\nbad old days, so it is! Haw haw!
What, me? I'm just a regular old pickaxe\nwho's working the mines to support\nhis little granddaughter.
Well, if ya say so. Just ease off on the\ndeath stare, will ya? It's givin' folks\na real case of the knock-knees.
...Not good. I need to watch it.

Still, sounds like we've got ourselves
a once and former troublemaker here.
Sure hope this new fella can keep
his past in the past...
